text: I'm glad this movie is coming out. So many people (mostly the young, uneducated and moronic ones) act like racism dividing the country is something new when it's been going on ever since slavery was abolished. I hate racism. It's so common that it's like it's in some people's DNA to just naturally dislike people of another race. Some people are racist and don't even realize it. I'll admit that there's been times when I'm sitting in my car and a black guy is walking by and I find myself reaching over to lock my car doors & I have to stop to tell myself that not every African American is a criminal. It makes me sad. Unfortunately that's just the way the world is and people can protest day and night for the next 200 years and it will NEVER end. The only thing we can do is to  always try and treat everyone no matter what race they are with respect and teach our children to do the same because there's nothing we can do about how others think, feel and act when it comes to race.

text: Is it about race or crooked police system? From my perspective, it is the latter, just the victim happens to be a black man, doesn't seem very special. Honestly, this movie is more of a fairy tale to me, wherein the case is open to public at the time, people are allowed to participate in some kind of march to express their disapproval, the victim himself gets to live to talk about it later when time allows, and most importantly, there's enough information left to let history judge. The reality is, in most countries on planet earth, this kind of story happens so often, people just gets numb about it: No one is able to reveal the truth, the ones that get remotely close get vaporized. It won't appear on newspaper and there will not be a single word about it in any historical document. I'm really surprised by the fact that people here in the U.S are allowed to talk about some very touchy topics(without worried about safely), and I think they should be grateful for this privilege.

It isn't, and he doesn't have much of a focus/presence in the film itself, though none of the actors really do (BTW I liked the film overall, but I would have preferred it if it was better advertised)
